Rating: 3
Reading the other reviews i was prepared to have runny stew. i thickened it by using extra tomato paste, coating the meat in flour and cornstarch, and using only 6 cups broth. i added some red wine which enhanced the flavor, and extra dash of worcestershire, and only four cloves of garlic. i also added more meat since the potato to meat ratio seems a little high. The recipe is a good base to start with, but without tweaking it would have been very watery. Everyone loved it and it's now a requested meal - i've made it twice since then. This dish is even better the following day. Definitely take the time to brown the veg! The second time around, to make the meat extra tender, i browned the meat and let simmer in the broth for an hour, cool and refigrated overnight. the following day i put it back on the stove and finished it off with more simmering and then added the vegetables and continued to cook as normal.

Rating: 4
thanks to all the other reviewers for their suggestions, this stew wouldn't be as good with out them. I've made this a few times, and here's what works for me: - definitely replace 1c. of broth with Guinness (I prefer over red wine for this) - Reduce total liquid to 5 cups (vs. the 8 called for) - Dredge the meat in flour before browning, but I find it may still need extra flour to thicken - don't skimp on browning the veggies, especially the carrots -the more garlic, the better - use 2 pounds of potatoes. ps this makes a HUGE pot. Some of the reviewers felt there was not enough meat, but I used the amount called for and thought it was plentiful, and sometimes I use even less.

