Rating: 0
While I have not made this recipe, I note that last reviewer claims to have made it. When the recipe calls for 2 tbsp of tomato paste, you added one 8 oz. can, halved the amount of beef broth, added red wine, mushrooms-- criminis and shiitakes (a real flavor- changer) and pearl onions. You did not make and rate the recipe given--you rated your own recipe.

Rating: 4
This stew is great with a few changes. I agree with many of the other comments. I used 2lbs. of Chateaubriand (very tender) dredged in whole-wheat flour with salt and pepper, 4 cups beef broth, 1 cup red wine, and a whole can of tomato paste as changes to the first half of the recipe. I sauted the meat and garlic in a dutch oven, (it sticks) but deglazed with the red wine before adding the rest of the ingredients. Brought it to a boil put the lid on it and then baked it at 325 degrees for 30 minutes. Meanwhile, I melted 2T butter and 2T oil in another big pan to saute 1/2 bag pearl onions and about 15 shiitake mushrooms (sliced) and about 15 cremini mushrooms (sliced). Then added 4 yukon gold potatoes (3/4 in. pieces) and the rest of the vegetables. (Seasoned with S & P.) Sauted the vegetables for another 15 minutes. After the meat cooked for the 30 minutes I added the vegetables to the stew and put it back in the oven for another hour. At the end I added the parsley and boy was it good! Enjoy!

