Rating: 4
My mum has made this stew for years and i would agree with the comments previously made,as we have used the same recipe(slightly less potatoes,more beef) but cook it slightly different. After browning and removing the meat,brown the veg and deglaze with half a can of guinness. Add the rest of the ingredients in a large pot with 1/4 bot of red wine and just cover with the stock. As t his recipe is meant to be cooked on a very low heat for 2/3 hours the amount of liquid should't then become a problem. For a real Irish touch i always add 1 1/2 cups of pearl barley. That reduces the liquid too. I love this stew. Great for cold days and works just as well with lamb.

Rating: 3
Here it is, Easter Sunday and our guests had to cancel so we had alot of extra lamb. I decided to try this based on the numerous positive reviews. I would give it 4 forks except I know people do not like high (or low) ratings when you've made alot of changes. Took others' advice: reduced the amount of broth, added red wine in place of one cup of broth, used fresh thyme instead of dried, reduced the amount of potatoes (used Yukon Gold...great). I added celery and will add parsnip next time for another level of flavor. Sauteed the vegetables but let them do most of the cooking in the stew. Dusted the meat with flour before browning...better flavor than adding corn starch...my husband hates all the "whites" but he thought the tiny bit of flour was fine. Fast, easy and delicious...with these changes, I'd highly recommend it to anyone but a novice could easily do it and impress.

