Rating: 4
I've been looking for a great beef stew recipe.(In Ireland the stew is typically made with lamb). Took the advice of the many reviewers and ended up with a fantastic rich meaty stew that is great with mashed spuds w/scallions or a nutty couscous dish. Here's what I did; Omitted the sugar and potatoes. Halved the garlic and beef stock. Used 2lbs of stewing steak and dredged in seasoned flour before sauteing. Added 2 stalks of chopped celery to the onion and carrot. MOST IMPORTANT added 2 cps of Guinness (bottle better than can). Cooked it all for about 4 hrs and it was fantastic! My mum loved it when she visited!

Rating: 4
We were looking for a dish for St.Patrick's day and this was perfect. We thickened it at the end with a little cornstarch water, and used fresh thyme but that was all for the change. It was delicious and we had lots of compliments

Rating: 2
I don't understand the high ratings, either. My parents were from Ireland, so I grew up with Irish food. As far as I'm concerned, it isn't Irish stew without the Guinness. I remade this omitting 2 cups of the broth and adding a 14 oz can of Guinness. I cut back on the garlic by half, even though I love it. I used one teaspoon of thyme and it was plenty. I also added salt and pepper to taste. There is no need for all that oil, either. I dredged the meat in flour before cooking it in about 3 tbsps of oil. The flour also serves to thicken the stew and more can be added if needed. I ended up adding a few tbsps more by first shaking it in a container with about 1/4 cup water. After adding it, bring the stew to a boil again for a few minutes. There is also no need to saute the vegetables first in even more fat. Just drop them in the stew after an hour and cook them until everything is tender. After making it this way, I had a stew that was bursting with flavor and the meat was very tender. Don't worry if the stew tastes bitter right after you add the Guinness. That will go away. Boiling also takes out all of the alcohol. My teenage son, who never eats much, ate two huge bowls of this.

Rating: 4
For our early Irish dinner, I made both the Irish lamb stew on this site and this beef stew along with the Irish Pub Salad and the soda bread. A friend made the Choclate Stout cake with sauce. The beef stew was terrific and I would make again - following suggestions from others to flour the beef, substitute brown sugar for granulated, add 1 T. molasses, extra stout beer for part of the beef stock, small red potatoes, and making a roux to thicken. It surpassed the lamb stew which was quite time-consuming to make, in flavor. Irish pub salad was a nice accompaniment and we added mashed potatoes since we were serving two stews on dinner plates. Great menu - cake the weakest. I also served three types of Irish cheese as appetizers.

