i also used about 3 pounds stewing beef. i also used about 5 red potatoes with the skin left on and i added some parsnips (because i like them). the thyme is a must as is the bay leaf but i didn't use worchestershire sauce or tomato paste (i had none) i used some chopped tomatoes and i dredged the beef in flour before browning. also added red wine to deglaze the pan and to the 8 cups of water i used one knorr beef bullion cube and some salt,too. it's really tasty even though i didn't follow the recipe exactly. i cut down on the oil too and didn't saute the veg. in butter.

Rating: 3
I made this again 12 months later and after many more reviews and tips. This time I used lamb, red wine, concentrated paste and cooked it for 21/2 hours. It was even better! I also made the Parsley Dumplings found under "Irish Stew" and they were very good also. Watch the size of those though so that they cook all the way through. Oh, and I agree with 2 lbs of meat, browned with flour and s&p, and I prefer less potatoes-just 2+ lbs.

Rating: 3
This recipe is great with a few alterations. Firstly, I use one small can of paste, 2 cups of red wine and more thyme. I also use a little more sugar. It is also very important to use Russett type potatoes and stew for at least 4 hours. If you do this, the spoon will stick up in the bowl like all great stew should, as my husband says.

Rating: 4
Easy to prepare, excellent aroma and final result very tasty. I followed others suggestions and dredged the beef in flour before cooking. I also used the oil from the stew to cook the vegetables, and cut down on the butter. I used a bit more tomato paste.

Rating: 3
I took many of the suggestions here and added some wine, and fewer potatoes. I also dredged the beef in a little seasoned flour before browning. I thought it was just so-so after the described amount of cooking time, so I set it aside for the following night. The next day, after simmering for another 2 hours or so the meat was almost ready to fall apart and the gravy had taken on a much richer flavour. Fantastic.

