Rating: 3
I agree with the review below mine, a good basic recipe. This is what I did differently, I sauteed the tomatoe paste (after the garlic) before adding the liquids, I then added a few splashes of wine. Then I added the broth, about 5 cups. I added marjoram and thyme. I used cornstarch to thicken the stew. When I sauteed the vegetables I added the same spices to the pan. I served it over a bed of rice and it was really good. My only advice in avoiding bland stews is to season it as you go along (including the meat - before browning).

Rating: 2
I thought this was a good basic stew. It was also interesting to make, the amount of thyme and garlic seemed excessive, but it worked. I was really intrigued by the frying of the vegies in butter, seemed like a great idea, however in the end I doubt it made much difference. I like my stew SPICY, and I think many cooks who make stews would have a hard time with this one, you know what you like, and this was not quite "it". However for someone new to a stew it was perfect. It was very good, well worthy of this site, but like many others, I will go back to what I like (I use curry, thyme, allspice, majoram, white pepper, cracked black pepper, red pepper flakes, cumin, fresh anything I can get, and almost always, even if I have to make a special trip to buy it: parsley at the very end). Stews are a wonderful meal, great for imagination and creativity. The day I insist that a stew follow a set of rules, I will hang up my apron! Finally, a fun thing to do with a stew such as this is to serve with some gremolata, why not?

